    value: 惶
english:
  title: A Memorial to the Government on Behalf of the Hall of Collected Writings
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Hall of Collected Writings existed in the previous dynasty, though its official titles were never true positions. From the Grand Academician down to the Academicians and Associate Academicians, all merely held nominal ranks concurrent with other offices. Eight scholars of civil service background divided among themselves the duties of historical record-keeping and literary affairs, advancing through their ranks in due course. Yet none were appointed to the regular consultative council. Thus authority lacked proper structure above, and below there was no lasting foundation.

    Those who held office merely sustained their roles, finding solace only in poetry and wine. Yet in those days they were honored most excellently—provided with official halls, lands, servants, and attendants. In time, however, the scholarly spirit grew corrupt. The dissolution became ever more pronounced, the negligence ever more extreme. The halls fell into disrepair unwended, escaped servants went untraced, public lands were seized, positions diminished—none of this was reported truthfully to court. Thus support and provision ceased altogether.

    Consider now the founding of our realm: desiring to promote learning, the court recognized our Hall's vacancy and established positions for officials of the third rank and above as true offices. Two Associate Directors were appointed with stipends. Yet fearing still a dearth of literary talent, scholars were attached from the Academy and Ministry of Appointments, burdened besides with drafting and secret records. We of meager ability dare not presume to fulfill such duties. Still, regarding the restoration of this neglected institution, we fear that amid pressing demands, much remains undone.

    Our sole petition concerns four matters aforementioned. Recently the court has graciously provided sustenance, yet the actual records languish in abandoned halls, and the historians sleep in cold chambers. With no public lands and no serving staff, how can this be called a proper office? Long have we endured these straits. We would not soil your hands with pleas for personal comfort—rather, because the nation's way of encouraging scholars should not be thus.

    We humbly beseech the government to preserve its compassion and implement these provisions item by item, thereby supporting the flourishing reign's promotion of culture. This would be most fortunate indeed. We bow twice in utmost reverence.
  footnotes:
    - The Hall of Collected Writings (Yeomun'gwan) was an important literary institution responsible for maintaining historical records and drafting state documents.
    - Lee Cham was a prominent early Joseon official and scholar during the reign of King Sejong, known for his advocacy of cultural and educational advancement.
    - The 'four matters' referenced are implied to concern the restoration of the Hall's physical facilities, recovery of lost properties and staff, and proper resource allocation.
